    "explanation": "<p>Given pole zero plot is shown in figure where the closed contour encloses 3 zeros and 2 poles in the $s$ plane.<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh201x4l/a1c92522-220f-4449-b209-632bde43df61/dbbcf250-af46-11f0-ba93-393527bdf085/file-jaoe38c1mh201x4m.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh201x4l/a1c92522-220f-4449-b209-632bde43df61/dbbcf250-af46-11f0-ba93-393527bdf085/file-jaoe38c1mh201x4m.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE ECE 2020 Control Systems - Root Locus Diagram Question 2 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>From principle of argument of Nyquist plot, if a closed contour encloses $P$ poles and $Z$ zero's in $s$-plane, then the origin of $G(s)$ plane is encircled $P-Z$ times.</p>\n<p>$$ N=P-Z $$</p>\n<p>$N=$ Number of encirclement of origin</p>\n<p>$N=$ Positive for counter clockwise direction</p>\n<p>Negative for clock wise direction</p>\n<p>Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;$$ P=2, Z=3 $$</p>\n<p>So,&nbsp;&nbsp;$$ N=2-3=-1 $$</p>\n<p>$$ \\text { Hence, the mapping will encircle origin of } G(s) \\text { plane in clockwise direction and option (D) is correct. } $$</p>",
