    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>The characteristic equation of a system is</p>\n<p>$$ s^3+3 s^2+(K+2) s+3 K=0 $$</p>\n<p>In the root locus plot for the given system, as $K$ varies from 0 to $\\infty$, the break-away or break-in point(s) lie within</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>$-\\infty,-3$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>$-3,-2$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>$-1,0$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>$-2,-1$</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Given : Characteristic equation is,</p>\n<p>$$ \\mathrm{C} . \\mathrm{E}=s^3+3 s^2+(2+K) s+3 K=0 $$</p>\n<p>Converting to standard form,</p>\n<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; s^3+3 s^2+2 s+K s+3 K=0 \\\\ &amp; s^3+3 s^2+2 s+K(s+3)=0 \\\\ &amp; 1+\\frac{K(s+3)}{s^3+3 s^2+2 s}=0 \\\\ &amp; 1+\\frac{K(s+3)}{s\\left(s^2+3 s+2\\right)}=0 \\\\ &amp; 1+\\frac{K(s+3)}{s(s+1)(s+2)}=0 \\end{aligned} $$</p>\n<p>The above equation is of the standard form,</p>\n<p>$$ 1+G(s) H(s)=0 $$</p>\n<p>Where, $G(s) H(s)$ is the open loop transfer function.</p>\n<p>$$ G(s) H(s)=\\frac{K(s+3)}{s(s+1)(s+2)} $$</p>\n<p>Drawing the pole-zero diagram,</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh23v1r0/4ed23d28-8c84-4f55-a197-891d3e1ae2cd/c1295dc0-af55-11f0-8ff7-4f6304b9a291/file-jaoe38c1mh23v1r1.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh23v1r0/4ed23d28-8c84-4f55-a197-891d3e1ae2cd/c1295dc0-af55-11f0-8ff7-4f6304b9a291/file-jaoe38c1mh23v1r1.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE ECE 2020 Control Systems - Root Locus Diagram Question 1 English Explanation\">The thick lines lies on Root Locus and thin lines does not lie on Root Locus. From the prediction of breakaway or break-in point, if there are consecutively placed poles on real axis, with the section of real axis between them as a part of RL then there exists at least one break-away or break-in points between them. Since, there are poles located at -1 and 0 , breakaway point will lie in between -1 and 0 .</p>\n<p>Hence, the correct option is (C).</p>",
